    "created_at": "2017-05-13T14:46:02Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-05-13T15:05:05Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Continuing from our earlier discussions, now that we have a plan for our naming conventions I think it would be best if the yaml interface for variables mirrored what we do for conditions.  For example:\r\n\r\n```\r\n PortableChrono:\r\n \tChargeDelay: 300\r\n \tChargeProgressVariable: charge-progress\r\n \tChargeDurationVariable: charge-duration\r\nConditionBar@PORTABLE_CHRONO:\r\n\tValueVariable: charge-progress\r\n\tMaxValueVariable: charge-duration\r\n\tColor: FF00FF\r\n```\r\n```\r\nExternalCondition@INVULNERABILITY:\r\n \tCondition: invulnerability\r\n \tTimerValue: invulnerability-remaining\r\n \tTimerDuration: invulnerability-duration\r\nConditionBar@INVULNERABILITY:\r\n\tValueVariable: invulnerability-remaining\r\n\tMaxValueVariable: invulnerability-duration\r\n```\r\nWe now only use timers for `ExternalConditions`, so we can put the variables there instead of on the `ConditionManager` (and rip out the timer support there).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThis makes the code self documenting, and removes the overheads of having a special dot syntax.\r\n\r\nFor the Health example I don't think we gain much from the special syntax over using regular conditions:\r\n```\r\nHealth:\r\n\tUndamagedCondition: no-damage\r\n\tLightDamageCondition: light-damage\r\n\t...\r\n\tCriticalDamageCondition: critical-damage\r\nGrantCondition@CRITICAL:\r\n\tRequiresCondition: critical-damage\r\n\tCondition: criticalspeed\r\n\tGrantPermanently: true # NOTE: must be added to GrantCondition\r\n```\r\n\r\nI concede that this might become too messy in other cases, so a simpler version of your example above could use variables paired with constants defined on the condition manager:\r\n```\r\nConditionManager:\r\n\tConstants:\r\n\t\tDamageState.Undamaged: 1\r\n\t\tDamageState.Heavy: 8\r\n\t\tDamageState.Critical: 16\r\nHealth:\r\n\tDamageStateVariable: damagestate\r\nGrantCondition@CRITICAL:\r\n\tRequiresCondition: damagestate >= DamageState.Critical\r\n\tCondition: criticalspeed\r\n\tGrantPermanently: true # NOTE: must be added to GrantCondition\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis is more flexible, but has the downside of requiring manual documentation about the different magic variable values."
  },
